---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const slug = 'cardiovascular';
const displayName = 'Cardiovascular';

const drugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(
  (d: any) => (d.organ_systems || []).includes(slug)
);
const drugCount = drugs.length;
---
<SchemaLayout title="Cardiovascular Pharmacology" schema="organ-systems" description="Drugs classified under the Cardiovascular organ system">

  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/01-organ-systems/`} class="link">Organ Systems</a></li>
        <li>Cardiovascular</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-base-content mb-2">Cardiovascular</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">{drugCount} drug{drugCount !== 1 ? 's' : ''} in this system</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>The cardiovascular system presents the richest pharmacological target landscape in clinical medicine, encompassing the heart's electrical conduction system, myocardial contractile machinery, peripheral vascular smooth muscle, and the coagulation cascade. Key drug targets include beta-1 adrenergic receptors on the sinoatrial and atrioventricular nodes and ventricular myocytes, the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) at multiple enzymatic and receptor nodes, voltage-gated L-type calcium channels in both cardiac and vascular smooth muscle, HMG-CoA reductase in hepatic cholesterol synthesis, and the coagulation factors that regulate thrombosis and hemostasis. Major disease states managed here include hypertension, heart failure with reduced and preserved ejection fraction, acute coronary syndromes, dysrhythmias, dyslipidemia, venous thromboembolism, and peripheral vascular disease. Nursing priorities for this system center on hemodynamic monitoring -- blood pressure, heart rate, rhythm, and perfusion signs -- as well as surveillance for bleeding with anticoagulants and antiplatelet agents, electrolyte shifts with diuretics and RAAS modulators, and fluid balance across the spectrum of heart failure presentations.</p>
    <p>Antihypertensive pharmacology spans six mechanistic classes whose selection is guided by comorbidity and evidence-based outcome data. ACE inhibitors and ARBs exert dual antihypertensive and reno-protective effects by reducing angiotensin II-mediated vasoconstriction and aldosterone secretion; they are preferred in patients with diabetes, CKD with proteinuria, and post-MI left ventricular dysfunction. Beta-blockers reduce heart rate and cardiac output while suppressing renin release, making them first-line after myocardial infarction and in heart failure with reduced EF. Calcium channel blockers relax vascular smooth muscle through L-type channel blockade and are particularly effective in isolated systolic hypertension and Prinzmetal angina. Diuretics reduce preload and plasma volume; thiazides are preferred for uncomplicated hypertension while loop diuretics are essential in acute decompensated heart failure. Nursing must assess for orthostatic hypotension with any antihypertensive class, recognizing that first-dose hypotension is most pronounced with alpha-1 blockers and after loop diuretic administration.</p>
    <p>Heart failure pharmacology targets the neurohormonal pathways that drive maladaptive cardiac remodeling: RAAS activation, sympathetic overstimulation, and aldosterone-mediated fibrosis. The foundational quadruple therapy for HFrEF -- ACE inhibitor or ARB-neprilysin inhibitor (sacubitril-valsartan), beta-blocker, mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, and SGLT2 inhibitor -- reduces mortality by 50 to 60 percent in aggregate. Digoxin, a Na+/K+-ATPase inhibitor that increases intracellular calcium and slows AV nodal conduction, remains useful for symptom control in HFrEF with atrial fibrillation but carries a narrow therapeutic index requiring serum monitoring at 0.5 to 0.9 ng/mL. Antidysrhythmic agents span four Vaughan-Williams classes, with amiodarone's complex class I, II, III, and IV effects making it the most broadly effective agent but also the most toxicity-prone, requiring thyroid, pulmonary, hepatic, and ophthalmological surveillance. Nurses managing anticoagulation must verify INR for warfarin (target 2 to 3 for most indications, 2.5 to 3.5 for mechanical mitral valves), and must teach patients that direct oral anticoagulants require no INR monitoring but must never be missed due to their short half-lives.</p>
  </div>

  {drugs.length === 0 && (
    <div class="alert alert-info mb-6">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
      <span>No drugs are currently classified under this organ system. Check back as more drug data is added.</span>
    </div>
  )}

  {drugs.length > 0 && (
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      {drugs.map((drug: any) => (
        <div class={`card card-compact bg-base-100 shadow border border-base-200 ${drug.ismp_high_alert ? 'border-l-4 border-l-error' : ''}`}>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-start gap-1 mb-1">
              <h2 class="card-title text-base font-semibold capitalize mr-auto">
                <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">
                  {drug.generic_name}
                </a>
              </h2>
              {drug.prototype_for && (
                <span class="badge badge-success badge-sm shrink-0">PROTOTYPE</span>
              )}
              {drug.ismp_high_alert && (
                <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm shrink-0">HIGH ALERT</span>
              )}
              {drug.black_box_warnings && drug.black_box_warnings.length > 0 && (
                <span class="badge badge-warning badge-sm shrink-0">BBW</span>
              )}
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-base-content/60 mb-1">
              <span class="font-medium">{drug.drug_class}</span>
              {drug.subclass && <span> &mdash; {drug.subclass}</span>}
            </p>
            {drug.mechanism_summary && (
              <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 line-clamp-3">{drug.mechanism_summary}</p>
            )}
            <div class="card-actions justify-end mt-2">
              <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="btn btn-xs btn-outline btn-primary">Profile</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  )}

</SchemaLayout>
